{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01465hroqFCXY1HUjKo4JTM5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to deploy a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster using native Kubernetes resources (no operators). Let me create:\n\n1. A ConfigMap for Elasticsearch configuration\n2. A headless Service for cluster discovery (es-transport)\n3. A Service for HTTPS access (es-http)\n4. A StatefulSet for the 3-node cluster\n5. A PodDisruptionBudget\n\nKey considerations for Elasticsearch 8.11.1:\n- TLS is required by default in ES 8.x\n- Need to configure inter-node TLS (transport)\n- Need to configure HTTPS for REST API\n- The existing es-http-tls secret provides the certificates I need for the HTTP layer\n- For transport TLS between nodes, I can reuse the same certificates or configure them separately\n- I'll enable xpack.security and set the ELASTIC_PASSWORD from the secret\n- The configuration needs xpack.security.enabled, xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled, and xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled all set to true\n- Since ES 8.x requires both HTTP and transport TLS, I'll use the same certificate set for both layers\n\nNow I'm designing the StatefulSet with the proper init containers and configuration... Configuring Elasticsearch security settings... Finishing the resource configuration with CPU limits, then setting up the volume claim templates for persistent storage. I'm also realizing I need to handle the `vm.max_map_count` sysctl setting that Elasticsearch requires—in a kind cluster this might need special handling at the node level rather than through an init container, though I could try using privileged mode. I should also verify what storage classes are available for the PVCs and think through the service definitions needed for cluster discovery. I'm weighing whether to use emptyDir for simplicity or PVCs for proper persistence—kind clusters typically have a `standard` storage class with local provisioning, so I'll go with PVCs. I also need to ensure the memory configuration is adequate; with a 2Gi limit, the JVM heap should land around 1Gi, which meets Elasticsearch's minimum requirements. I should also configure the bootstrap memory lock setting to prevent swapping.\n\nNow I'm setting up the manifests: a ConfigMap for the Elasticsearch configuration, a headless service for cluster discovery, a ClusterIP service for HTTP access, and a StatefulSet to manage the pods. The configuration will include cluster settings, security with TLS certificates, and proper discovery configuration.\n\nWriting manifest templates... I'm realizing that Elasticsearch 8 supports environment variable substitution directly in the configuration, so I can leverage that instead of trying to manage everything through a ConfigMap. The key is understanding the correct format for passing settings as environment variables to ES, which should align with how the application expects them.\n\nWriting the StatefulSet manifest... I'm realizing that environment variables with dots might cause issues in Kubernetes, so I should use a ConfigMap instead to mount the elasticsearch.yml configuration file directly. This approach is more reliable than trying to pass dotted variable names through the container environment. I'll use environment variables to set the node name dynamically from the pod metadata, and configure the network to listen on all interfaces so the cluster can communicate properly within Kubernetes. Then I'm setting up the final elasticsearch.yml configuration with all the SSL certificates and cluster settings, along with the environment variable injection for the node name. I need to use `subPath` to mount just the elasticsearch.yml file without shadowing the entire config directory, and I'll set up separate volume mounts for the config file and TLS certificates. Now I'm thinking through the resource requests and limits for the Elasticsearch containers.\n\nFor a test environment with limited resources, I'll set the JVM heap to 512m with container memory requests at 1Gi and limits around 1.5-2Gi to avoid OOM issues that would prevent Elasticsearch from starting.\n\nNow I need to write out the complete manifests and apply them, starting with a single YAML file containing all the resources. I'll also check what storage options are available before deciding between persistent volumes or emptyDir for the StatefulSet.\n\nOne thing I should account for is the `vm.max_map_count` sysctl requirement that Elasticsearch needs. In kind clusters running on Docker, I might need to set this on the node itself, possibly through a privileged init container that adjusts the kernel parameter.\n\nFor the TLS setup, the `es-http-tls` secret contains the certificate and key for the HTTP server, plus the CA certificate. I need to make sure the certificate is valid for the pod's hostname so clients can verify it properly.\n\nI'll configure transport SSL with `verification_mode: certificate` to validate the cert against the CA without strict hostname checking, which should work with the existing certificate. Now I'm ready to write out the final manifests, starting with a ConfigMap for the Elasticsearch configuration and the rest of the deployment setup. Finishing the transport SSL configuration and setting up the Kubernetes services for Elasticsearch cluster communication and client access.\n\nNow I'm adding a PodDisruptionBudget to ensure at least two replicas stay available during disruptions, then defining a StatefulSet with three replicas that uses the headless service for discovery. I'm also configuring an init container to set the required kernel parameter for memory mapping.\n\nConfiguring Elasticsearch container... Finishing the StatefulSet configuration with volume claim templates for persistent storage and TLS certificate setup. Now I'm reconsidering the TLS certificate—the pre-created cert in es-http-tls might be bound to a specific hostname like `es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, and I need to verify it matches what the client will actually use when connecting.\n\nFor transport layer SSL with certificate verification mode, hostname validation won't be enforced, so as long as the cert is signed by the CA, it should work fine. I'm also thinking through the readiness probe—the curl command needs curl to be available in the Elasticsearch container, which the official 8.11.1 image does include, so that should be fine.\n\nLet me apply these manifests and first check what storage classes are available in the cluster.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":290,"cache_read_input_tokens":29926,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":290},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1dbbafb2-5c68-4053-909c-600bf0cd1e93","uuid":"a9c55ed9-7ea2-4acf-ac01-ee7f2a7f2b3c","request_id":"req_011CbzK3pJTPdAf53K9BPTYe"}
